# History
The building that now houses the Community Centre was built in 1857, and opened as a Church of England School in 1863.

When it was closed in the 1970s, local people formed a Charitable Trust with a view to retaining the building as a community resource and focal point.

In 1980 it re-opened as a Community Centre. By the main door, there is a plaque installed to commemorate this event which was unveiled by famous local sculptor and artist [Josefina de Vasconcellos](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josefina_de_Vasconcello) whose works include [Reconciliation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reconciliation_(Josefina_de_Vasconcellos_sculpture)) at Coventry Cathedral and the Hiroshima Peace Park in Japan.

The building is currently leased from the Diocese of Carlisle on an annual rent, this cost along with the maintenance and upkeep are paid for through community fundraising and usage fees.

## Today
The future of the Hall as a centre for the Skelwith Community is in question. Even before Covid, usage was down, and rent maintenence and utility costs are rising. Last year, the Trust Committee came to the reluctant conclusion that there is not enough income from fundraising and regular bookings to justify the substantial long term cost of maintaining the Hall.
At the Annual General Meeting, the community was asked if the Hall should be closed and the lease given up.
The fairly strong feeling of that meeting was that a final attempt should be made to re-invigorate the Hall and several new members joined to committee with a view to making that happen. In 2022, we intend to do our best to assess and, if possible, enhance the value of the Hall as an asset for our community.

### How to help
2022 will be a crucial year for decisions about the Hall and the most important thing is to use the hall for as many events as possibe, follow our [Facebook page](https://www.facebook.com/skelwith) to find out more about fortcoming events.

If you have ideas for new uses for the hall, or would like to hire it for a private event or run a community event please let us know. Any current member of the committee: Christine, Jess, Geoff, Giles, Martin, Michael, Neil, Peter, Sue or Rob would be really happy to talk to you about any ideas you have - new committee members are also always welcome!
Alternatively, you can email us at: trust@skelwith.community

# Hiring the Hall

The Community Centre is run by a charitable trust for the benefit of everyone in the surrounding area.

The Hall is available for a range of events, including:
- __Community Events__ organised by individuals or groups for the benefit of the whole community.
- __Commercial Hire__ for private usage by organisations providing commercial or stautory services.
- __Private Hire__ for events like parties

## Cost

Current hire rates are __£15/hr__ for __Commercial__ and __Private__ hire, and __£6/hr__ for __Community__ groups and events to which all in the local community are welcome.

The hire costs are set at this level in order to help us cover some of the substantial costs of leasing, maintaining and operating the Community Centre. They are heavilly subsidised by donations and fundraising events throughout the year.
Notwithstanding this, the Centre is a charity which is run for community benefit, so if these costs represent a barrier to your using the Hall, and your usage has a wider community benefit then please contact us and we will do our best to try and accomodate you.

The Community Centre is situated in the Parish of Skelwith in the heart of the Lake District. Just 150m off the main A593 Ambleside to Coniston Road at Skelwith Bridge, it is uniquely accessible for users from the area west of Windermere.

Originally built as the village school in 1857, since 1979 it has been run by a charitable trust to provide a focal point for the surrounding rural district community. 

Community groups, commercial organisations and individuals can hire the building and its environs for events, educational classes or meetings, all at a reasonable cost.
